{"/service/ndnp/ct/batch_ct_carpsurprise_ver01/data/sn85009852/00517174907/1958032701/0138.xml":{"full_text":"PAGE FOUR\nThe East Hart lord Gazette\nEstahusnea in 1884 By Henry B Haie ruonsnea every i nursday ai\nWK Main Street, hast Harttord, Connecticut. Enteru as second class\nmatter at the Post Office in Hartford on December 2. 1842 under tne Act\nOf March 3. 1879.\nAll news contributions and releases, excnanses and oustness com\nmunications should Oe addressed to tne East Hartford Gazette. 1128\nMain Street, East Hatrtoru. Connecticut. telephone JAekson 82194\nSubscription rate: S3.OU per year, So.au tor two years, $7 50 foi three\nyears; servicemen and teachers, $2.00 per year.\njonn G. Kobrbacb. General Manager\nJohn W. McLean. Editor\nJoyce Rossignol, womens Editor\nPublished by the West Hartford Publishing Company. Bice C'lemow,\nPresident; Henry E. Griffith, Vice President.\nToo Much Delay\nOn School Budget\nThe Board of Finance and\nBoard of Education were sched\nuled to meet in joint session\nWednesday night. As this is\nwritten, before the meeting, one\nthing already can be said about\nit for certain: It is being held\ntoo late.\nThe corresponding joint meet\ning last year was held March 9,\ntwo and one-half weeks earlier.\nFinal action on the 1957-1958\nBoard of Education budget was\ncompleted by the Council March\n23. This year it looks as if\nthere will be no action until\nApril 15.\nThese delays may not seem\nlong. But they are crucial to the\norderly hiring of teachers. For\nthe past month or more the\nBoard of Education has been hir\ning teachers without a firm sal\nary schedule for next fall. This\nmeans that if the budget which\nis finally approved does not al\nlow the Board of Education to\npay the $4,100 starting pay it\nwants to\u2014and hardly anyone\nthinks the Finance Board will\napprove the full school budget\u2014\nthe teachers hired so far might\nnot really be hired.\nYet it does no good to say\nthat Superintendent John A.\nLangford should just wait until\nfinal action before seeking the\nnew teachers the system needs.\nThis is the time the best teach\ners are being hired. If you don\u2019t\nget them now, you don\u2019t get\nthem later.\nThe Board of Education fin\nished its budget action on Feb\nruary 4. There is no excuse for\nthe Board of Finance to wait a\nmonth and a half before sitting\ndown with Board of Education.\nNew Elks Lodge\nA Source Of Pride\nThe Elks officially came to\nEast Hartford last weekend. The\nGazette believes the towm will\nreap great benefits from the\nestablishment of 8.P.0.E. Lodge\nNo. 2063.\nSince their founding in 186 S,\nthe Elks have promoted good\nfellowship among their members\nand valuable service to the na\ntion, and to communities with\nlodges.\nThe order has spent more than\n$110,000,000 for benevolent pur\nposes. Much of this has been\nthrough its justly famed jjouth\nactivities, which serve some\n2,500,000 youngsters each year\nElks scholarships and Elks essay\nand oratorical prizes are among\nthe most coveted.\nAnd in more intangible ways,\nElks lodges have been a force\nfor good. They have consistently\npromoted the best in their towns.\nThey have bestowed recognition,\nthrough invitation to member\nship and election to office, on\nmen of solid worth. Their club\nhouses have often provided the\nforum for informal civic dis\ncussion which leads eventually\nto major achievements.\nThe lodge in East Hartford be\ngins under splendid auspices. A\ncore of East Hartford Elks who\nbelonged to other lodges, princi\npally Manchester\u2019s Lodge No.\nwith some 300 members. Among\nthem are many of the town\u2019s\nleading citizens.\nEnthusiastic community accept\nance of the new lodge is indi\ncated by the 172 page instal\nlation program, made possible\nby many hundreds of advertisers\nand boosters.\nAnd already members of the\nlodge are afire with plans for\ncommunity activities.\nOn top of the direct service\nthey may fender, the East Hart\nford Elks Lodge will be a good\nthing just because it is there.\nIt is another fine group which\nEast Hartford can call its own.\nIt is another testimony to the\nspirit and cohesiveness of the\ntown.\nThe Gazette salutes Lodge\n2063. Good luck!\nSplit In Town GOP\nMay Strengthen Party\nIn politics, internal warfare is\na strange thing. Sometimes it is\ngood. Sometimes it is bad.\nFacing what most observers\nthink will be a banner year for\nthem, Connecticut Democrats\nlook for unity.\nThe party leadership has kept\nhands off the fight fdr the Sen\nate nomination fearing a split.\nSheriff Donald Potter, one of\nTHURSDAY, MARCH 27, 1958\nseveral candidates for the con\ngressional nomination, told East\nHartford Young Democrats last\nThursday night that party unity\nwas the key to success. Demo\ncrats are perfectly willing to ar\ngue over candidates, but not\nwith such vigor that the party\nmechanism is torn apart.\nJust the opposite is happening\nto the Republicans in East Hart\nford. The party so far has not\nendorsed state-wide candidates.\nIt hasn\u2019t publicly, and perhaps\nnot privately, come up with as\npirants for the Legislature. But\nit is engaged in an internal bat\ntle over whether Town Chair\nman William C. Caplin shduld\nbe unseated by Anthony Poly\ndys.\nAnd this argument, many\npeople agree, is good for the Re\npublicans. Not because it may\nresult in the ouster of Mr. Cap\nlin. But because it may stir up\nparty spirit which has been\nsomewhat dampened by two suc\ncessive defeats in town elections.\nThe two-party system, Ameri\nca\u2019s greatest contribution to the\nart of politics, depends for its\nsurvival on how losing parties\nconduct themselves. Had not Re\npublicans done the best they\ncould for their party after Lan\ndon's defeat, there would have\nbeen no Eisenhower Republican\nvictories in 1952 and 1956. Had\nDemocrats given up after Eisen\nhower, their chances would not\nlook so good for 1960.\nSo what East Hartford Repub\nlicans do now, when their\nchances of gaining office are not\ntoo promising, is important for\nthe future. It is not the role of\na town newspaper to endorse\ncandidates for party posts, as it\ndoes for public office. But the\nGazette does express the hope\nthat out of the present Republi\ncan conflict will come a strong,\nunited party which will be able\nto mount the effective challenge\nto the Democrats that true func\ntioning of the two-party system\nrequires.\n20 Years Ago\n(from April 1, 1920)\nEight local high school stu\ndents have brought East Hart\nford the State Championship in\nthe \u201cBig Apple Dance.\u201d Compet\ning in a contest in Waterbury\nin February against teams from\nall over Connecticut, the local\nyouths won the championship\nand a prize of SSO. The members\nof the dancing team are: Thelma\nWalker, John Devaney, Rita Pel\nletier, Wiliam Foley, Mercedes\nMurphy, Wally Hart, Bubby\nHeal, and Joseph Birtle.\nMr. and Mrs. Bertrand Cooper\nand family of Ambrose Terrace\nspent last weekend at their cot\ntage at Lake Otis, Mass.\nMrs. Alfred H. Rood has re\nturned from a trip to Florida.\nMiss Marjorie Molaison was\nguest of honor at a birthday\nparty Wednesday given for her\nat her home by her parents, Mr.\nand Mrs. Frank Molaison and\nher brother, Frank Molaison Jr.\nThe guests included: Mrs. Paul\nRamsdorf, Miss Frances Rams\ndorf, William Ramsdorf, Fred\nKlein. Miss Mary O\u2019Brien and\nMiss Dorothy Demkey.\nMiss Charlotte Francis of 425\nMain Street spent several days\nin New York City last week.\nWith three of its 48 original\ncharter members present the\nAuxiliary of Brawn-L ande rs,\nAmerican Legion Post, observed\nits tenth anniversary Saturday\nevening. Over 100 members and\nguests were present. The three\ncharter members were Mrs. Han\nmer, Mrs. Mary McCauley, a\nGold Star Mother, and Mrs. Pearl\nLord.\n40 Years Ago\n(from April 12, 1918)\nMrs. E. O. Goodwin and daugh\nter returned a few days ago\nfrom Atlantic City.\nThe New Haven office of the\nNava! Reserve has enrolled in\nthis town Frank C. Schleicher\nand Henry R. Hayden.\nGeorge Lawton of High Street\nhas purchased a new Oldsmobile\nroadster.\nSaturday evening in Wells\nHall the Farm Bureau of the\nlohal auxiliary of the Connecticut\nState Council of Defense met and\nperfected plans for the war rally\nthat was held in Comstock Hall\nWednesday evening. The commit\ntee consisted of Clarence J. Can\nnon. Charles R. Risley, Archie\nJ. Evans, William K. Ackley,\nLevi P. Hickey and Edward E.\nKing. The committee is perfect\ning plans for the raising of food\nstuffs in this town during the\ncoming season, and is planning to\ncarry out the agricultural survey\nin accordance with instructions\nfrom the Council of Defense.\n\u201cIf It Works Out, It\u2019ll Be A Nice Change\nj'~\u2014\u2014\u2014ZZ s\n'''iZ/Vjlt\n-Z7 ///I 1 1\n^S. -IM a\ne# Rm\niV 4-11\n\u2014f r~ i\n-\u25a0\u2014\"\"T j\nMent.'s.' Ixl U\nDrew Pearson says:\nEconomic situation prompts\nserious split in Cabinet\nWashington Reason for\nconflicting statements out of\nthe White House on the busi\nness recession last week was\na serious split inside the Cab\ninet, plus the fact that bad\nnews has penetrated through\nthe WTlite House guard with\nfull force to Ike himself, and\nhe is alarmed.\nJust one week ago Ike\u2019s Secre\ntary of the Treasury Bob An\nderson had gone to his fellow\nTexan, Speaker Sam Raybum.\nand patched up a truce regard\ning taxes. Rather than have\nDemocrats and Republicans out\ndoing each other in promising\ntax cuts, they agreed to say no\nmore, do no more regarding tax\ncuts without prior notification.\nFour days later this truce was\nbroken by the President himself.\nSenate Republican leader Bill\nKnowland. leaving the White\nHouse after a long conference\nwith the President, announced\nthat it would be at least two\nmonths before the administra\ntion makes a decision on cutting\ntaxes.\nThe Knowland statement came\nat 12:11 noon. At 12:59 noon the\nPresident promised a group of\ncheering Republican women that\nhe would cut taxes if neces\nsary.\nThis threw the tax-cutting fat\nright back into the fire. It also\nignored the private warning\nfrom Detroit automobile manu\nfacturers that talk of taxes only\nheld back the buying of automo\nbiles. The public, they warned,\nis not going to rush to buy cars\nas long as they can hope for al\nS2OO reduction of excise taxes'\nper car.\nWAR AGAINST RECESSION\nMeanwhile, the White House\nresembles Ike\u2019s SHEAF offices\nduring the Battle of the Bulge.\nEconomic reports are scanned\nas anxiously as were scanned\nthe reports from the 106th Di\nvision or Gen. Tony McAu\nliffe's 101st Airborne Division\nduring that crucial battle in\nthe Ardennes forest around\nChristmas of 1944.\nWhat the President\u2019s economic\nadvisers are watching are:\n1. New construction contracts\n2. New business orders\n3. Insurance companies\u2019 invest\nment plans\n4. Advance financing for new\nhome construction\n5. The fluctuation of the stock\nmarket.\nThey believe these give the\nbusiness barometer better than\nunemployment figures.\nSo far, the barometer is not\nhopeful. Employment usually\nrises in March with spring con\nstruction, but unemployment fig\nures so far, though scattered,\nshow a continued rise in claims\nfor unemployment insurance and\na continued drop in income. This\nindicates that more people are\nlosing their jobs and that those\nwho are keeping their jobs are\ngetting either pay cuts or less\novertime.\nSPLIT IN CABINET\nMeanwhile, here is how the\nCabinet is split right down the\nmiddle regarding the business\nslump:\nGo-slow Group\u2014 The majority\nCabinet group believes in taking\nno hasty action until mid-May.\nThey are more worried over in\nflation than depression, believe\nthe administration was panicked\nback in 1953-54, moved too quick\nly to head off a recession, with\nthe result that the recession\nwas \u201covercured\u201d and started\nprices on their inflationary spir\nal. They don\u2019t want to make\nthis mistake again, are willing\nEAS^HARTFO?* GAZETTE,-EAST HARTFORD, CONN\nto gamble that the economy will\n\\pull out of its slump. A tax cut\nnow. they argue, would start a\ni chain reaction, unbalance the\nbudget, lead to higher prices,\nmore inflation.\nChief architect of this Wait\nand-see philosophy is White\nHouse economic adviser Gabriel\nHauge, the pipe-smoking, tweed\nsuit economist who has been\nwith Ike since the beginning.\nHis chief support comes from\nSherman Adams, wiry, square\ndancing. efficient ex-Governor\nof New Hampshire, now the\nmost powerful man in the White\nHouse on domestic policies, bar\nnone. Supporting them is Bob\nAnderson, the Texas rancher\nand oilman, now Secretary of\nthe Treasury whose job it is to\nraise the money. If he was the\ni nervous type, he\u2019d lie awake at\nI night worrying where the money\n|is coming from\u2014if Congress si\nmultaneously cuts taxes and\ngoes on a spending spree.\nPercival Brundage, the Direc\ntor of the Budget who bowed\nout of office suddenly, agreed\nwith this group up until a few\ndays before his resignation.!\nThen he flew into a panic over\nthe plunging economy and\nswitched frantically to the move\nnow group.\nSignificantly. William McChes\nney Martin, chairman of the\nLetters\nFrom Our\nReaders\nMinutes and Milk\nTo the Editor:\nAccording to information pre\npared by Prof. Stewart Johnson\nof the University of Connecticut\nand being distributed by Con\nnecticut dairies under the title\n\u201cConnecticut Milk Facts,\u201d con\nsumers are told that the \u201creal\u201d\nprice of milk is measured in the\nnumber of minutes a person\nmust work in order to buy a\nquart of milk. In this summary,\nProf. Johnson has used Connec\nticut figures only. We think it is\nonly fair to compare these with\nother markets.\nFor instance, in Connecticut\nthe average worker receives\n52.1 l per hour. At 28c per quart\n(or 51.12 a gallon) he works 8\nminutes in order to purchase a\nquart of milk. In Akron, Ohio,\nan average worker earns $2.57\nan hour, can purchase milk for\n68c a gallon, thus working 4.1\nminutes in order to purchase a\nquart of milk. In Chicago, 111.,\nthe average worker earns 52.33\nan hour, can purchase milk for\n79c a gallon; he works 5.1 min\nutes to purchase a quart of\nmilk. In Springfield, Mass., the\naverage worker earns 52.03 an\nhour and can purchase milk for\n82c gallon, he works 6 minutes\nto purchase a quart of milk.\nThese figures are taken from\nthe February issue of the U.S.\nDepartment of Labor publica\ntion \u201cEmployment and Earn\nings\u201d based on December, 1957.\nand from the U. S. Department\nof Agriculture \"Fluid Milk and\nCream Report\u201d for December.\n1957.\nSo it seems that if you live in\nConnecticut, you must still pay\na higher price for milk, based\neither on dollars and cents or\nminutes work.\nMRS. BARBARA SANZO\n1 Federal Reserve Board, brother\nt in-law of Sir Roger Makin, the\ni ex-British Ambassador in Wash\nington now charged with watch\ning British economy, is a mem\nber of the go-slow group. The\nFederal Reserve Board is sup\nposed to be independent of the\nI Administration, but there was\nnote-comparing under the Demo-\ni crats as there is under the Re\npublicans today. Martin believes\ni the recession may have a\nhealthy effect on the economy\nin the long run by forcing prices i\ndown. He wants to wait and see.!\nAlso belonging to the wait-and-|\nsee group are Secretary of Com\nmerce Sinclair Weeks, the blue\nblood Boston Banker, silver man\ns ufacturer and director of the!\nBoston Herald and Traveler; to-i\ngether with sincere, conserva\nr five Secretary of Agriculture Ez i\nra Taft Benson.\nThe Move-now Group Chief\nI advocates of drastic anti-reces\nsion action inside the Cabinet I\nare Secretary of Labor Jim Mitch\ndell and Secretary of the Interi-I\nI;or Fred Seaton. The President's!\nI chief economic adviser. Raymond!\nJ Saulnier, has been cautious, hut!\nfavors certain anti recession!\nI moves.\nWhat worries the move-now\ngroup is that the present reces\nsion shows signs of being much\nmore severe than those of 1948\n49 and 1953-54. Basic difference\nis that this recession has been\ncaused partly by a slowdown in\ncapital goods. Manufacturers\nhave been ordering less material\nto produce consumer goods and\nthe economists claim this is a\nbad sign.\nAnnual Sing\nIs Set Sunday\nAt Burnside\nThe United Protestant Choirs\nof East Hartford will present\ntheir Palm Sunday concert Sun\nday at 7:30 p.m. at Burnside\nMethodist Church. The public is\ninvited.\nThe presentation will be the\nsacred cantata, \u201cThe Crucifix\nion,\u201d by John Stainer.\nTwo professional soloists will\nbe featured. Dr. Clyde Keutzer,\nthe director of the Hartford\nSchool of Music, will sing the\ntenor solos. John Kerr will sing\nthe baritone solos.\nMr. Kerr is soloist at the First\nCongregational Church in New\nBritain.\nHe sings with the Hartford\nSymphony Chorale, and has\nsung with the Simsbury Light\nOpera Co. Both soloists have\nsung with this group before.\nThe mixed group of about 80\nvoices repre ents the seven lo\ncal Protestant churches. It is un\nder the direction of Miss Doris\nRayner, director of music at the\nFirst Congregational Church of\nEast Hartford, and director of\nmusic in East Hartford public\n.schools.\nMrs. Louise Hazzard, organist\nof Hockanum Methodist Church,\nwill play the accompaniment for\nthe cantata. Mrs. Lola Johnston,\norganist of the Burnside Meth\nodist Church, 'will play the pre\nlude and the postlude.\nMrs. Vera Minor, organist of\nthe First Congregational Church,\nwill play the offertory. Justin\nTaft, director of music of the\nSouth Congregational Church,\nwill play the rsrc^ mniment for\nthe general singing. 5\nChurch Notices\nST. CHRISTOPHER\nRev. Henry J. Murphy, Pastor\nMasses will be said at the\nchurch each Sunday at 8,9,\n10:10 and 11:15.\nConfessions 4, 5:30, 7:30, 9 p.m.\nST. ROSE CHURCH\nRev. Austin Munich, Pastor\nSunday masses at 7. 8:15.\n9:45, 11 a.m. in the church. 8:15,\n9:45 in St. Rose School.\n8 and 10 a.m. at auditorium\nof the Administration Building\nin Mayberry Village. Confession.\nSaturday 3:30, 5:30, 7:30 and 9\np.m.\nBLESSED SACRAMENT\nRev. Henry J. Murphy, Pastor\nMasses at 7:30, 8:30, 10 and 11\nin the church.\nConfessions 4. 5:30, 7:30, 9\np.m.\nST. MARY\u2019S CHURCH\nMsgr. Thomas J. Drennan,\nPastor\nSunday masses at 7,8, 9,\n10 and 11.\nMasses at St. Mary\u2019s School at\n9:05 and 10:05 a.m.\nMass at Meadow School, 8, 9\na.m.\nConfessions Saturday 3:30, 5\n7:30 and 9.\nST. FRANCIS ASSISI\nSouth Windsor\nRev. Arthur J. Heffernan, Pastor\nSunday masses at 7,8, 9, 10\nand 11 a.m.\nConfessions Saturday, 4, 5:30.\n7 and 9.\nHO( KANUM METHODIST\nCharles S. Johnson, Pastor\nSaturday\u2014Rangers food Sale\nSunday\u2014B:2o, Men's Commun\nion Service and Breakfast at\nBurnside Church. 9:30, Churcii\nSchool classes for all ages. 10:45,\nChild Care Center. 11, Morning\nWorship and Meditation \u2014the\nPalm Tree. 6, Intermediate Fel\nlowship.\nThursday Holy Communion\nSendee at 7:30.\nFriday\u2014Three hour service at\nSt. John\u2019s Church.\nWESLEY MEMORIAL\nMETHODIST\nMatt Mees, Minister\nThursday, March 27\u2014Senior\nChoir Rehearsal.\nFriday, March 28\u2014Sub-District\nRally\u2019 MYF at Hazardville.\nSaturday, 9 a.m., Junior Choir\nRehearsal.\nSunday, March 30\u2014Palm Sun\nday\u2014The Choirs will sing \"The\nPalms.\u201d 9:30 and 11 a.m.. Ser\nmon meditation, \"The Word of\nConviction.\u201d 9:30. Sunday School\n\u2014Harry Huntington, general su\nperintendent.\nMonday, Song and Prayer Cir\ncle, 7:30 p.m.\nTuesday, Commission on Mis\nsions, 7 :30.\nThursday\u2014Maundy Thursday.\nReception of Members and Holy\nCommunion.\nFIRST C ONGREGATIONAL\nTruman H. Woodward, Pastor\nSunday, March 30\u20149:30. Wor\nship in the chapel. 9:30, Church\nschool. 10:45, Child-care center\nopens. 11, Worship in the sanc\ntuary. 6:30, Pastor\u2019s Class: \u201cCon\ngregational Church Govern\nment.\u201d \u201cThe Sacraments.\u201d 7, Pil\ngrim Youth Fellowship.\nMarch 31, (Monday) 6:45,\nTroop No. 49. Girl Scouts.\nTuesday, April 1\u20146:30, Guik\nGroup of Women\u2019s Fellowshij\npotluck supper. Mr. Woodwai\nwill speak on a Lenten theme\nWednesday, April 2 I:3C\nThreeScore-Plus Club. 3:1.'\nTroop No. 312, Brownies. 6:l*\nYouth Choir rehearsal. 6:30,\nr it\nHURTS!!\nIt really hurts\u2014the high cost of\nthings you have to buy.\nThat goes for a steel company, too.\nThe steel people are in exactly the\nsame kind of squeeze everybody else\nis\u2014and on a bigger scale because\nthey have to buy so much.\nEven little things. Take the cost of\nthe thousands of brooms that the steel\ncompanies buy in a year to keep their\nplants clean. Ten years ago a good\nindustrial broom could be bought for\nAMERICAN IRON AND STEEL INSTITUTE\n150 East Forty-Sacond Straat, Naw York City\nJunior Pilgrim Youth Fellow\nship;, CIHU Club. 7:30, Chorus\nchoir rehearsal.\nThursday, April 3\u20141:30, Mary\nand Martha Bible Study Group.\n7, Troop No. 1, Boy Scouts. 7:30,\nCandlelight Communion Service.\nSpeaker: The Rev. George Rob\nerts of West Hartford. 10:30 a.m.\nKing\u2019s Daughters. Hostesses are:\nMrs. Edgar S. Abild, Mrs. Leon\nNoble, and Mrs. Arthur Cowles.\n7:30, The standing committee\nwill be omitted.\nSunday, April 6, 6 a.m.. Sun\nrise service at Veteran's Memori\nal Park. Please note the change\nin time.\nST. JOHN\u2019S EPISCOPAL\n-Rev. Sherman W. Andrews,\nRector\nPalm Sunday, March 30\u20148,\nHoly Communion; 9, Morning\nPrayer and Church School;\n10:15, Morning Prayer and\nChurch School. Palms to be giv\nen out at all services will be\nblessed at the 8 a.m. service.\nMonday\u2014Holy Communion at\n8 a.m.\nTuesday\u2014Holy Communion at\n5:30 a.m.\nWednesday\u2014Holy Communion\nat 9:30 a.m.\nMaundy Thursday\u2014Holy Com\nmunion at 7 a.m. and 7:30 p.m.\nGood Friday Community\nThree Hour Service from 12 to\n3 p.m.. Evening Service at 7:30.\nEaster Even\u2014Holy Baptism at\n4 p.m.\nSOUTH CONGREGATIONAL\nRoger S. Nicholson, Minister\nThursday, March 27\u2014\u201c What\nDo Protestants Believe?\u201d a dis\ncussion group led by Mr. Nichol\nson at 8 pm.\nSaturday, March 29 Confir\nmation Class at 9 a.m. God and\nCountry Award Class at 10 a.m.\nSunday, March 30\u2014Palm Sun\nday Morning Service of Wor\nship 9:30 and 11 a.m. Sermon:\n\u201cChrist Was Born for This\u201d by\nMr. Nicholson. The youth Choir\nand the Chancel Choir will sing\n\u201cThe Palms\u201d by Faure. Junior\nChoir will sing at 11. Church\nSchool at 9:15 at the Goodwin\nSchool. Child care lor infants up\nto two at 9:15 and 11 at the\nchurch. Nursery and Kindergar\nten Departments at 9:15 and 11\nat the church. An orientation\nmeeting at 4 p.m. for new mem\nbers joining the church on April\nHAYDEN HALL\nCHOCOLATES\nBy Burnham Brady\nOne pound: 51.50\nSteel... metal of a million utet\nTHURSDAY, MARCH 27, 19S8\n3, Maundy Thursday. Youth\nChoir rehearsal at 5. Pilgrim\nFellowship at 6 for regular\nmeeting and then attend the\nUnited Choir program.\nMonday, March 31\u2014Board of\nTrustees at 7:45.\nWednesday, April 2 Adult\nStudy Group at 8 p.m.\nThursday, April 3\u2014Maundy\nThursday Holy Week Commun\nion Service and Reception of\nNew Members at 8 p.m.\nBURNSIDE METHODIST\nMinister, John E. Post\nAssistant Minister,\nFrederick C. Allen\nThursday, March 27\u20142 p.m.,\nHanmer Circle in Scudder\nRoom. 6:45 p.m., Girl Scouts in\nYouth Center.\nSaturday, March 29\u20149 a.m.,\nChildrens\u2019 Choir rehearsal; 10\na.m., Confirmation Class for In\ntermediates; 7 p.m., United\nChoirs rehearsal.\nPalm Sunday. March 30\u20149:30\nand 11 a.m., Morning worship\nwith nursery\u2019 care. Sermon by\nthe Rev. Dr. Charles X. Hutch\ninson, Jr., on the topic \"De\nliver Us From Evil.\u201d Sacrament\nof Baptism and Reception of\nYouth into Church: 6:30 p.m..\nLast Junior Lenten Service. Mite\nboxes will be collected.\nMonday, March 31\u20148 p.m.,\nConversation Group.\nWednesday, April 2\u2014lo a.m.,\nWomen\u2019s Prayer Group in De-\nMars Chapel; 7 p.m., Rehearsal\nfor Tenebrae Service; 7:30 p.m.,\nPastor\u2019s Cabinet in Scudder\nRoom.\nRev. G. Uno Landmark, Pastor\nFriday, March 28th 8 p.m.\nCouples\u2019 Club. Rev. Dean Peter\nson, missionary to Africa, guest\nspeaker.\nSaturday, March 29th\u20149 am.\nJunior Confirmation; 10:15 a.m.\nSenior Confirmation.\nSunday. March 30th\u20149:30 a.m.\nChurch School at Sunset Ridge\nSchool; 9:30 and 11 a.m Sendee\nof Divine Worship with Nursery.\nWednesday, April 2nd\u20147 pm\nChanel Choir; 8 p.m. Senior\nChoir.\nThursday. April 3rd 8 p.m.\nHoly Communion Sendee.\nNAMED TO GROUP\nHenry T. Coleman of 4 Rox\nbury Road. East Hartford CPA,\nhas been elected a member of\nthe American Institute of Certi\nfied Public Accountants. Mr.\nColeman is associated with the\nfirm of Knust, Everett Cam\ni bria In Hartford.\n$1.27. That broom today costs $1,95.'\nOr look at the tires for steel com\npany trucks. A 10-ply tire was $66.50\nten years ago. Same tire today, 1\n$122.30. Other costs are \u2019way up, too, 1\nlike raw materials and all the other\nthings steel companies buy to the tune\nof several billions of dollars a year. 1\nNo wonder it costs more to make steel\nthese days.\nEverybody feels it when costs are\nhigh industries as well as people.\nFAITH LUTHERAN\nOn Sale At:\nEast Hartford\nBurnside Drug\nCurtiss Pharmacy\nKay Drug\nPat\u2019s Medical\nPharmacy\nProspect Pharmacy\nThomas A Hanmer\nDelicious fresh choco\nlates, made right in\nHartford avail\nable in 4 different\nselections; assorted\nchocolates; all-creams;\nnut. crisp chewy;\nand all-milk choco\nlates.","height":"26892","width":"20028"}}
